    • 1960 — 1969

    Click on any release to be taken to the corresponding release on the Releases page.

    Key to symbols:

    • † after an issue number denotes the lack of an official catalogue number (e.g. it may be a marking on the record surface but not on the record label)
    • * after release denotes that only part of the take has been used for the issued title
    • ‡ indicates a release is not confirmed
    • ◊ indicates the first issue
    • # is added to a title to distinguish it from a different tune of the same name
    • * after a New DESOR number indicates it is not from the New DESOR or a correction sheet, but has been unofficially assigned elsewhere
    • External links have the following codes
      • (D): Discogs.com
      • (MB): MusicBrainz.org
      • (A): Amazon (US)
      • (AM): AllMusic
      • (AR): Archive.org
      • (F): Misc file
      • (S): Spotify
      • (T): Tidal
      • (YT): YouTube

    61-07-30-001CO67172-Asphalt Jungle ThemeDE6114a
    61-07-30-002CO67855-Asphalt Jungle ThemeCBS 88654(D), Co 4-42144◊DE6114b
    61-07-30-003CO67855-Asphalt Jungle ThemeCBS 62993, CBS 88654(D), Co 4-42144◊, Co CL-1765DE6114c
    On the AFofM Recording Report of this date, DE6114a is listed as “Asphalt Jungle Theme Part I” (remake of June 1); DE6114b is listed as “Asphalt Jungle Theme Part II, Version I” and DE6114c is listed as “Asphalt Jungle Theme Part II, Version II”, but they are issued as “Asphalt Jungle Theme Part I and Part II” on Co 4-42144. The doubt persists that 6114a instead of 6114b was published in Co 4-42144. DE6114c is titled “Asphalt Jungle Twist” on Co CL-1765 and CBS 62993.

    The copyright organization SESAC engaged Duke Ellington to provide music during the annual convention of the National Association of Broadcasters. Here we present the actual dates, 6 and 7 April, and possibly the correct sequence of performances. They were not known when NDESOR IDs were assigned, so that they appear out of sequence between the two dates.

    65-06-20-002TPA5-3356House Of LordsBb 09026-63953-2, Bb 2178-2-RB, Ms MCD-1012, RCA 09026-63386-2(D), RCA LPM-3499DE6539c

    65-06-20-003TPA5-3353The Second Portrait Of The LionBb 09026-63953-2, Bb 2178-2-RB, Ms MCD-1012, RCA 09026-63386-2(D), RCA LPM-3499DE6539d
    NDESOR authors decided to remove Sweet Lorraine (DE6539b), because a non-Ellington item, Correction Sheet 5005. Ben Young in the liner notes of Bb 09026-63953-2 explains: «The Pittsburgh Piano Workshop was so spontaneous that Billy Taylor’s announcement of a Hines-Ellington duet was followed instead by Sweet Lorraine, a Taylor and Hines duet. The location engineers were confused and left Ellington’s name alongside Sweet Lorraine on the tape box, which explains why this item was long thought to include all three pianists.»

    65-07-31-005Aaron Copland’s “Preamble For A Solemn Occasion”DE6545e
    The concert took place on July 30 and was repeated on July 31, and it is possible that these recordings were made on July 30. In “Preamble For A Solemn Occasion” Ellington recites the text, an extract of the United Nations’ Declaration of Human Rights, that is integral part of Aaron Copland’s composition.
